,"1432":"1432","1531":"1531","1385":"1385","about 1420":"about 1420","ABT 1437":"about 1437","1429":"1429","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","abt 1432":"about 1432","of Much Marcle, Hrfrd, Engl":"Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England":"Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walwyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wal(d)wine</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, from elements meaning ‘power’ + ‘friend’.","from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Walweyn</i>, <i>Walwain</i>. The central French form of this name is <i>Gawain</i> (see   Gavin  ). This name is found in the medieval Arthurian romances and is traditionally explained as an adaptation of the Welsh name <i>Gwalchmei</i>, perhaps meaning ‘hawk of the plain’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gavin","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gábháin</b> or <b>Ó Gáibhín</b>, both of which are derived from diminutives of <i>gábhadh</i> ‘want’ or ‘danger’ (the second being the more likely meaning here).","Scottish and northern English: from the personal name <i>Gavin</i>, Scottish form of English <i>Gawain</i> and French   Gauvain  . The name was introduced into English from French versions of the Arthurian romances, where this name was borne by one of the knights of the Round Table, brother of Galahad and Mordred and a nephew of Arthur. It has been taken to be an adaptation of the Welsh name <i>Gwalchmei</i>, perhaps ‘hawk of the plain’.","Scottish: shortened form of   McGavin  , which is believed to be an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b> ‘son of the smith’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Walwyn was born in 1405, his father, William Walwyn, was 20 and his mother, Isabel Baskerville, was -2. He married Isabel Baskerville about 1420, in Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1405–":"1405–Surnud","1405–Male":"1405–Surnud","1407–Female":"1407–Surnud","1429–1531":"1429–1531","1432–Female":"1432–Surnud","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1437":"1437","1432":"1432","1531":"1531","1385":"1385","about 1420":"umbes 1420","ABT 1437":"umbes 1437","1429":"1429","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","abt 1432":"umbes 1432","of Much Marcle, Hrfrd, Engl":"Much Marcle, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England":"Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1405–":"1405–Kuollut","1405–Male":"1405–Kuollut","1407–Female":"1407–Kuollut","1429–1531":"1429–1531","1432–Female":"1432–Kuollut","1437–Male":"1437–Kuollut","1385–Male":"1385–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1432":"1432","1531":"1531","1385":"1385","about 1420":"noin 1420","ABT 1437":"noin 1437","1429":"1429","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","abt 1432":"noin 1432","of Much Marcle, Hrfrd, Engl":"Much Marcle, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England":"Much Marcle, Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"1405–":"1405–Décédé","1405–Male":"1405–Décédé","1407–Female":"1407–Décédée","1429–1531":"1429–1531","1432–Female":"1432–Décédée","1437–Male":"1437–Décédé","1385–Male":"1385–Décédé","1437":"1437","1432":"1432","1531":"1531","1385":"1385","about 1420":"environ 1420","ABT 1437":"environ 1437","1429":"1429","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","abt 1432":"environ 1